From Background Script or Content Script
Send a Message: Use chrome.runtime.sendMessage() to tell the side panel to close itself.
javascript
// In background.js or content.js
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({ action: 'closeSidePanel' });
Listen for the Message: In your sidepanel.js, listen for this message and then close the panel.
javascript
// In sidepanel.js
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener(message => {
  if (message.action === 'closeSidePanel') {
    window.close();
  }
});

Using setOptions to Hide (Disabling)
While not strictly "closing," you can disable the side panel for a specific tab, effectively hiding your extension's panel.
javascript
// In background.js
chrome.sidePanel.setOptions({
    tabId: tab.id, // Target the specific tab
    enabled: false // Disable the panel
});
This removes your panel from the tab's list but keeps the window open, requiring window.close() to truly dismiss the UI. 
Important Note
The chrome.sidePanel.close() method mentioned in some older discussions is not yet widely available or standard for closing other panels; window.close() from within the panel's context is the common pattern.

